"" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 404 "N.B.  There are vario
us questions and properties about prime numbers which are of interest \+
and study.  For example, it is known that there are infinitely many pr
imes.  There is only one even prime. (Why?)  The distribution of the o
dd primes is not fully understood.  If two consecutive odd numbers are
 both prime (e.g., (5,7) ; (17,19), (101,103)), then such a pair of co
nsecutive odd primes is called a " }{TEXT 282 19 "pair of twin primes
" }{TEXT -1 174 ".  It is not known whether or not there are infinitel
y many such pairs of twin primes.  It is known that there can be arbit
rarily large gaps between consecutive primes.  Etc." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 372 "5.  Relatively Prime N
umbers.  Two positive integers are said to be relatively prime if the \+
only positive integer which (evenly) divides both of them is 1.  Examp
les of  (pairs of) relatively prime integers are:  74, 51;   13, 120; \+
  344280, 267317.  If two integers are relatively prime, then the grea
test common divisor of the two integers must be 1.  The maple command \+
" }{TEXT 278 3 "gcd" }{TEXT -1 296 " can be used to determine whether \+
greatest common divisor of two integers is 1, i.e., whether the two in
tegers are relatively prime.  Show that each of the above mentioned pa
irs of integers are relatively prime.  Find three other pairs of relat
ively prime integers with the following constraints:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "
