{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 3 "6. " }
{TEXT 267 33 "Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic" }{TEXT -1 148 ".  The
 Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic states that every integer can be fa
ctored in a unique way into a product of powers of primes.  For exampl
e:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 1 " " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 5 "84 \+
= " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "``(2)^2*``(3)*``(7);" "6#*(-%!G6#\"\"#F'-F%6#\"\"$
\"\"\"-F%6#\"\"(F+" }{TEXT -1 4 " ;  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 9 "2
8490 =  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 "``(2)*``(5)*``(7)*``(11)*``(37);" "6#*,-%!G6
#\"\"#\"\"\"-F%6#\"\"&F(-F%6#\"\"(F(-F%6#\"#6F(-F%6#\"#PF(" }{TEXT -1 
4 " ;  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 21 "5813258142483000  =  " }
{XPPEDIT 18 0 "``(2)^3*``(3)^4*``(5)^3*``(11)^2*``(23)^3*``(29)*``(41)
^2;" "6#*0-%!G6#\"\"#\"\"$-F%6#F(\"\"%-F%6#\"\"&F(-F%6#\"#6F'-F%6#\"#B
F(-F%6#\"#H\"\"\"-F%6#\"#TF'" }{TEXT -1 4 " .  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 17 "It is called the " }
{TEXT 270 11 "Fundamental" }{TEXT -1 217 " Theorem of Arithmetic becau
se of the role it plays in both simple and deep results in algebra and
 number theory.  There are numerous and important facts which follow b
ecause of  the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 10 "          " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 111 "Use paper and
 pencil to factor the following integers into their prime decompositio
ns:  340340, 38*865, 10!.   " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 266 24 "Answers:2^2*5*7*11*13*17" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 10 "2*5*19*173" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 13 "2^8*3^4*5^2*7
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 19 "The M
aple command  " }{TEXT 268 7 "ifactor" }{TEXT -1 32 " does this automa
tically.   Use " }{TEXT 269 7 "ifactor" }{TEXT -1 102 " to verify your
 results from above.  Now factor the following numbers:  384*8650,  10
!+1 ,  your ss#. " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "ifactor(340340);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#*.)-%!G6#\"\"#F(\"\"\"-F&6#\"\"&F)-F&6#\"\"(F)-F&6#\"#6
F)-F&6#\"#8F)-F&6#\"#<F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 
"ifactor(38*865);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#**-%!G6#\"\"#\"\"
\"-F%6#\"\"&F(-F%6#\"#>F(-F%6#\"$t\"F(" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 14 "ifactor (10!);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#**)
-%!G6#\"\"#\"\")\"\"\")-F&6#\"\"$\"\"%F*)-F&6#\"\"&F(F*-F&6#\"\"(F*" }
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }
{TEXT 286 2 "kp" }{TEXT -1 38 "  you didn't factor  10! + 1      -1/2
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 384 "7.  \+
Greatest Common Divisors and Least Common Multiple (and the Fundamenta
l Theorem of Arithmetic).  Maple can compute for a pair of integers (a
,b) both the greatest common divisor of  (a,b) and the least common mu
ltiple of (a,b) easily.  The commands for doing so are gcd(a,b) and lc
m(a,b), respectively.  For each of the following pairs (a,b) find both
 the gcd(a,b) and the lcm(a,b)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 105 "a.  74,148           b.  201, 1001      \+
   c.  202, 1002     d.  2432902008176640000,41758540970065920000" }}
